   THRIFTS IN LIMBO: S&amp;Ls hobble along while awaiting
government sale.
   Some 256 S&amp;Ls thrash in conservatorship, a kind of
no-saver's-land between receivership and going on the block.
"It's like a ship with no rudder" staying open pending sale,
says Richard White, president of Midwest Federal Savings,
Minot, N.D. Resolution Trust Corp. sends a managing agent who
often curtails activity. Generally not allowed: new loans;
maturities beyond six months; top rates or ad promotions.
That makes it tough to keep even the most loyal customers.
"We're not competitive," sighs Mr. White. Deposits fell 10%
to $510 million at Midwest since the end of 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   George Bragg, new president of Sooner Federal in Tulsa,
Okla., visited every one of the thrift's branches to stem
outflows last year. "I talked with 900 customers," says Mr.
Bragg, who also has had political aspirations. Sooner lost
$80 million of its $1.2 billion in deposits. Managers also
fled, but he says the thrift "spread responsibility" and now
has "a more efficient staff." RTC, meanwhile, speeds up
sales.
   RTC figures 60% of the thrifts were "victimized by
criminal activity."
                                                                                                       

   FIDO'S A FATSO, say pet food companies pushing new "lite"
products.
   "Lots of cats and dogs sit with their owners and watch TV
when they used to be out chasing birds," says Elizabeth
Hodgkins of Hill's Pet Products. To combat an "epidemic of
overweight," the Colgate-Palmolive unit offers high-fiber,
low-fat "maintenance" pet food as well as prescription
products. Ralston Purina adds Pro Plan Lite for cats on the
paws of Tender Vittles Lite. Purina's Fit &amp; Trim for dogs --
its pioneer product -- is still a big seller in the $5.8
billion supermarket pet food field.
   Snacks are always a problem: one extra-large Milk-Bone has
254 calories. Ms. Hodgkins suggests withholding some of
doggie's canned food, baking it and "cutting it into little
bites" for treats. Wesley Bayles, a Washington, D.C., vet, is
more generous, but he confesses to being overweight himself.
"My evaluation of a dog's weight may not be the same as some
skinny veterinarian's." His own black Lab manages to stay a
trim 72 pounds on dog food and the odd pizza crust.
                                                                                                       

   FIRST-DAY DOCS lay hands on patients this month. Should
you be one?
   The academic year begins in teaching hospitals as interns
fresh from medical school join newly-advanced residents in a
changing-of-the guard. Turnover of the so-called house staff
means a patient can have one team of doctors on June 30 and
another on July 1 -- provoking anxiety all around. But a
recent study led by Dr. Eugene C. Rich of the University of
Kentucky College of Medicine, found that quality of care
didn't suffer during the summer months. However, the length
of hospitalization rose -- and so did the bill.
   The report, published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, drew criticism from Dr. Jeffrey L.
Kaufman, of Albany (N.Y.) Medical College, for counting
readmissions, death and nursing home placement rather than
more relevant criteria like quality of written orders or
correctness of drug dosage. His advice? Ask your doctor if
the hospital has a transition strategy. If not, "I'd say wait
a little bit." If so, "it's perfectly reasonable to go in."
Dr. Sol Sherry, former chief of medicine at Philadelphia's
Temple University Hospital, says overlapping the teams helps
greatly.
   "It's a pressure cooker," Dr. Sherry says of the
transition. But "we never had a great problem."
                                                                                                       

