   HAZARDOUS TO YOUR LOAN: Concern over toxic materials
clouds lending.
   Commercial loans and multifamily housing projects have
been subject to environmental audits for some time. Now, as
lists of hazardous substances and potential liabilities grow
well beyond asbestos and radon, some lenders feel the home
mortgage may be the next big risk. There aren't the typical
business-site hazards, "but more lenders are becoming more
sensitive to other kinds of problems," says Warren Tyler of
State Savings Bank, Columbus, Ohio.
   Mr. Tyler, a former state EPA director, predicts lawn
chemicals and drinking water are the next potential concerns.
Others point to backyard, underground fuel-storage tanks. In
Massachusetts, state law says prospective homeowners must
agree to remove lead-based paint from certain surfaces if a
child under six will live in a house built before 1978. But
enforcement has been feeble. Part of the problem: budget
cuts.
   Chemical Bank's first-stage environmental audit for a
multifamily project costs $2,000 to $3,000.
                                                                                                       

